{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17655196","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17655196"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T22:00:32+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T22:00:32+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18653"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"18653","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/18653"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.04,0.15,0.11,0.7,0]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11385"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77672"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"11385","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/11385"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18653"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63185"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4926"},{"type":"tags","id":"4931"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"6682"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"26398"},{"type":"contributions","id":"26679"},{"type":"contributions","id":"26918"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77672","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/77672"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EThe major arteries of the upper limb follow a predictable course and provide essential blood supply to the arm, forearm and hand.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the correct anatomical relationship of the major arteries in the upper limb?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Brachial artery divides into radial and ulnar arteries at teres major muscle","Axillary artery becomes brachial artery at the first rib","Radial and ulnar arteries form digital arteries at the wrist","Brachial artery divides into radial and ulnar arteries in the cubital fossa","Axillary artery becomes brachial artery in the forearm"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe correct anatomical relationship is that the \u003Cstrong\u003Ebrachial artery (image) divides into radial and ulnar arteries in the cubital fossa\u003C/strong\u003E. This division occurs at the level of the neck of the radius.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBrachial artery divides into radial and ulnar arteries at teres major muscle\u003C/strong\u003E - This division occurs much more distally in the cubital fossa\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAxillary artery becomes brachial artery at the first rib\u003C/strong\u003E - The axillary artery becomes the brachial artery at the inferior border of teres major muscle, not at the first rib\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERadial and ulnar arteries form digital arteries at the wrist\u003C/strong\u003E - The radial and ulnar arteries first form the deep and superficial palmar arches respectively, which then give rise to digital arteries\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAxillary artery becomes brachial artery in the forearm\u003C/strong\u003E - This transition occurs much more proximally at the inferior border of teres major muscle\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EUnderstanding these relationships is crucial for clinical procedures and assessment of upper limb circulation.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["The transition from axillary to brachial artery occurs when the vessel passes the lower edge of teres major muscle.","The bifurcation of the brachial artery into radial and ulnar branches takes place within the cubital fossa.","In the hand, the radial artery contributes to the deep palmar arch while the ulnar artery forms the superficial palmar arch."],"references":["Netter FH. Netter Atlas of Human Anatomy: A Regional Approach with Latin Terminology. Eighth edition. Elsevier; 2022.","\u201cBrachial artery\u201d by Henry Vandyke Carter is under\u00a0Public Domain. \u003Chttps://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:Brachial_a.png\u003E"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63185"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18653"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"21436"}]}}},{"type":"media","id":"21436","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/21436"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/1AfjWr6Yso6AXW01celRwxpJm6oObX.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/1AfjWr6Yso6AXW01celRwxpJm6oObX.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":640,"height":669}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63185","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/63185"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-07T21:30:49+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-07T21:31:37+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11385"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77672"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":n